A slight modification from https://stackoverflow.com/a/57111010. The trick is that the `-usepretex` option is necessary to tell latexmk to actually do what you specified in `-pretex`


    set file = &quot;Document&quot;
    latexmk -pdfxe -jobname=${file}&quot;-v1&quot; -pretex=&quot;\def\testcs{1}&quot; -usepretex ${file}

Instead of hooking the `NativeLoader.loadLibrary(&quot;my-lib&quot;)` into life cycle hook of spring I used static context.

```java
static {
    try {
        NativeLoader.loadLibrary(&quot;my-lib&quot;)
    } catch (IOException ex) {
        throw new ExceptionInInitializerError(ex);
    }
}
```

The main thing is using [`ExceptionInInitializerError`][1] which is built for this kind of static context initializations.

So when using `@MockBean`, spring does run `@PostConstruct` in each test (As it should clean the application context from mocked components), but the loading of the library happens once. 

  [1]: https://docs.oracle.com/javase/7/docs/api/java/lang/ExceptionInInitializerError.html

